How I know she's full of shit: "we only use this steel once."

Melting down, and recycling steel does not reduce the quality of the steel, as long as your using the same manufacturing process as the first time.

You know why there are only a handful of steel mills in the US? Because you don't need to mine/refine as much anymore. The steel that's used in every tool/car/bridge/road sign is the same steel they took out of the ground to make fighter planes in ww2. 

Fun fact: manufacturers of Geiger counters and other radiation detection equipment use steel from sunken ww1&2 era ships. Reason being, after the atomic bombings in Japan, and all the subsequent cold war atomic tests, there's no material left on the planet that's not slightly radioactive. If they used regular steel those detectors wouldn't work because they'd just detect themselves.

video_title: DON'T USE DRYWALL ANCHORS! Try This Instead! (MOUNTING PLATES--Stud In The Wrong Place)
text:
Wall anchors and toggle bolts are not bad options whatsoever….its simply that people underestimate the weight that will hang their, and install them incorrectly 80% of the time.

  1.) Wall anchors - the golden rule here is called “power of 3”, which simply means that whatever weight you believe needs to hang from the anchor, get one that can hold triple that weight.
   Secondly, choose a pilot hole but that is barely smaller than the anchor size. This way, you can tap the anchor into the wall with a rubber mallet so it is snug, secure, and has zero wiggle room, thereby insuring the screw expands and gains maximum outward tension against the drywall.

2.) Toggle bolts - for starters, accurately discern what length of machine screw is needed for the distance between the drywall and whatever is being fastened to it. Getting a 4” toggle bolt for standard 5/8 drywall is overkill and the screw could punch through something you can’t see going in.

   Secondly, the power of 3 still applies. If I’m hanging a 40 pound TV wall mount bracket, I’ll use 4 or 5 quarter inch toggle bolts. One of these can home up to 80-120 lbs a piece. Using 5 in a rectangle formation with one in the middle can now handle 500 plus pounds.
   God himself would struggle removing it.

  Finally, buy your wall anchors and toggle bolts from an online specialty fastener store like Uline, Fastenal, or Grainger. They are head and shoulders above Home Depot and Lowe’s, will last forever, and a come in packs small or large enough for any usage.

  Wall anchor and toggle bolts are not inferior, the people whose ignorance about installation and placement technique generally are.

The top two shelves should have been configured like the work bench 4/8/4 rather than 8/8.   it makes no sense to have two cantilevers meet in  the middle rather than a solid span above the bench with two 4' wide towers on each side. 
Bins can be stacked.  The top shelf is not necessary.  And it's omission would allow the header above the bench to be raised  5" to avoid head bumps.   
A bench height of 38' to 44" is more ergonomic for standing work and provides space for two roomy shelves under the bench.
Using wall studs for support is efficient provided fasteners shear strength exceeds loads.  Rec 4 1/2" lag screws.

text: Since you mentioned threaded rod. You can get something called a Sammy. It’s a thick beefy lag with a thick and deep hex bolt head. Pre-drill your joist (and use a Drill not an impact, it will over torque your threads and them weaker). It has internal threads that you can use threaded rod with. They make it for all your standard hardware sizes, but 3/8 will do just about everything you need it to. It’s a great price of hard ware. Deep strut is also a good one, as it’s also considered a framing material.
